tspan.tspan: You can hear when the wind picks up or feel cool/warm air when the air conditioner kicks on, but you can't see it. When you try to study fluid
flows, this can be frustrating. After all, seeing is believing. A fundamental property of supersonic flows is the presence of strong gradients. That is,
large differences in pressure, temperature, or density. Now, let's back up a little and think about a cup of water with a straw in it. If you're looking
directly at this cup, the straw seems to bend but when you pull it out of the water, it looks fine! This is the effect of refraction. That is, light will
bend differently depending on the density of the medium it passes through. While our jet uses only one medium, air, it generates some strong
density gradients! When light passes through these regions in the flow, it bends and changes the light captured by a camera! this forms the
basis of shadowgraph flow visualization. The image above shows a sample image of flow from the diamond nozzle I am studying. Top row:
